`std::fs::metadata()` includes permission info too. You can check if a file is read-only by looking at the `permissions` field:

  ```rust
  let meta = std::fs::metadata("path/to/file").unwrap();
  let perm = meta.permissions();
  if perm.readonly() {
      println!("File is read-only");
  } else {
      println!("File is writable");
  }
  But wait, a quick clarification: `Permissions` has a method `.readonly()` which tells you if the file is set to be read-only. But changing permissions isn’t straightforward.

  If you want to make a file read-only or writable, you’d use `std::fs::set_permissions()`. Here's an example:
  ```rust
  let mut perm = meta.permissions();
  perm.set_readonly(true);
  std::fs::set_permissions("path/to/file", perm).unwrap();

Absolutely! Permissions can vary slightly between files and directories due to platform differences.

  On Unix-like systems (Linux, macOS), directories have different permission bits compared to regular files. For example, you might want to check if a directory is writable:
  ```rust
  let meta = std::fs::metadata("path/to/dir").unwrap();
  let perm = meta.permissions();
  if !perm.readonly() {
      println!("Directory is writable");
  }

  On Windows, permissions work differently. You need to use `winapi` or `ntdll` for more fine-grained control.

  One thing to watch out for: setting permissions on certain files may require elevated privileges. Always handle errors gracefully!
